.TH "CONFFLE" 5 "February 2026" "atomdns" "atomdns authors"

.SH "NAME"
.PP
\fIconffile\fP \- configuration file for atomdns

.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.PP
A \fIconffile\fP specifies the handlers atomdns should chain. The syntax is as follows:

.PP
.RS

.nf
ZONE [ZONE]... {
    [HANDLER]...
}

.fi
.RE

.PP
Such a section is called a \fIhandler block\fP. Each block defines the handlers this server should run
when it gets a query for the \fBZONE\fPs.

.PP
The \fBZONE\fP defines for which zones this handler should be called, multiple zones are allowed and must be
\fIwhite space\fP separated.

.PP
When a query comes in, it is matched again all zones for all handlers locks, the block with the longest match for the
query name will receive the query.

.PP
\fBHANDLER\fP defines the handlers(s) we want to load. This is optional as well, but a block with no handlers
will just return REFUSED for all queries. Each handler can have a number of properties that can have
arguments, see the documentation for each handler (atomdns\-\fBHANDLER\fP(7)).

.PP
The order of the \fBHANDLER\fPs is the order in which they are executed! (If you know CoreDNS, this is
different, as which CoreDNS the order is fixed compile time). I.e. putting the \fIlog\fP handler (atomdns\-log(7))
as last, means no queries are logged.

.PP
Comments are allowed and begin with an unquoted hash \fB\fC#\fR and continue to the end of the line. Comments may be
started anywhere on a line.

.PP
Environment variables are supported and either the Unix or Windows form may be used: \fB\fC{$ENV_VAR_1}\fR or
\fB\fC{%ENV_VAR_2%}\fR.

.PP
The \fB\fC~\fR (tilde) character and path names will be expanded to the home directory of the current user.

.PP
As an way to test things Conffile also supports a shorter way of writing things, but this only works for a
single handler:

.PP
.RS

.nf
ZONE [ZONE]...
[HANDLER]...

.fi
.RE

.PP
I.e.

.PP
.RS

.nf
example.org
log
whoami

.fi
.RE

.PP
Is a valid configuration and is supported by \fB\fCatomdns\fR.

.SH "GLOBAL"
.PP
A Conffile must have a global block, this is a section without a zone and holds various server wide
options, like how many instances, if you want DOH and DOT servers, etc. etc. For each server type (DNS, DOT
and DOH) you have a section \fB\fCdns\fR, \fB\fCdot\fR, \fB\fCdoh\fR and \fB\fCdou\fR where you can configure the server, most notably the
address and port you want to listen on.

.PP
.RS

.nf
{
    dns {
        addr [::]:1053
    }
    root /var/lib/atomdns
    metrics localhost:9153
}

.fi
.RE

.PP
See atomdns\-global(7) for more information.

.SH "IMPORT"
.PP
You can use the \fIimport\fP "handler" to include parts of other files, or snippets that are defined in the
configuration file see atomdns\-import(7). To prevent infinite recursion a maximum of a 1000 imports are allowed.

.SH "SNIPPETS"
.PP
If you want to reuse a snippet you can define one with and then use it with \fIimport\fP.

.PP
.RS

.nf
(mysnippet) {
    log
    whoami
}

example.org {
    import mysnippet
}

.fi
.RE

.SH "EXAMPLES"
.PP
The \fBZONE\fP is root zone \fB\fC.\fR, the \fBhandler\fP is \fIchaos\fP. The \fIchaos\fP handler takes an (optional) argument:
\fB\fCatomdns-001\fR. This text is returned on a CH class query: \fB\fCdig CH TXT version.bind @localhost\fR.

.PP
.RS

.nf
\&. {
   chaos atomdns\-001
}

.fi
.RE

.PP
When defining a new zone, you either create a new block, or add it to an existing one. Here we define two
blocks that each handle a different zone, that potentially chain different handlers:

.PP
.RS

.nf
example.org {
    whoami
}
org {
    whoami
}

.fi
.RE

.PP
But this is identical to:

.PP
.RS

.nf
example.org org {
    whoami
}

.fi
.RE

.PP
Reverse zones can be specified as domain names:

.PP
.RS

.nf
0.0.10.in\-addr.arpa {
    whoami
}

.fi
.RE

.PP
Or by just using the CIDR notation:

.PP
.RS

.nf
10.0.0.0/24 {
    whoami
}

.fi
.RE

.PP
This also works on a non octet boundary:

.PP
.RS

.nf
10.0.0.0/27 {
    whoami
}

.fi
.RE

.PP
Doing Let's Encrypt certificates for your DOH servers:

.PP
.RS

.nf
{
    root /var/lib/atomdns

    dns {
        addr [::]:1053
        limits {
            tcp \-1
            run numcpu()*3
        }
    }
    doh {
        addr [::]:10053
        limits {
            run numcpu()*1
        }
    }
    tls lets\-encrypt {
        source eth0
        contact miek@miek.nl
        path lets\-encrypt
    }
}

example.net {
    log
    dbfile example.net
}

.fi
.RE

